{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471604"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"378"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/378"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.06,0.24,0.16,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45468"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/378"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"367"},{"type":"tags","id":"2143"},{"type":"tags","id":"2290"},{"type":"tags","id":"2868"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"9690"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44027"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45468"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman brings her seven-year-old grandson to their General Practice clinic as she is concerned he is not \u0027growing properly.\u0027 She has raised him from birth as his parents both have an intellectual disability. His medical history is unremarkable. He does not take any regular medications. On examination, his height is on the 3rd percentile and his weight is on the 10th percentile. Review of his growth chart shows he has never crossed two percentile lines. The mid-parental height is unknown. His grandmother reports that he is otherwise well and \u0027he eats like a healthy boy should.\u0027 A left hand and wrist X-ray shows a bone age of 5.5 years.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Poor growth","Klinefelter syndrome","Growth hormone deficiency","Familial short stature","Constitutional delay"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests knowledge of the differential diagnoses for short stature in paediatrics. The key features are that this child has short stature with \u003Cstrong\u003Edelayed bone age\u003C/strong\u003E but is otherwise completely well. A child with these features is most likely to have \u003Cstrong\u003Econstitutional delay\u003C/strong\u003E. Constitutional delay is a benign condition characterised by a slow rate of growth but with a good long-term height prognosis. The bone age is delayed compared to chronological age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAssessment of \u003Cstrong\u003Efamilial short stature\u003C/strong\u003E would be aided by knowing the mid-parental height. However, regardless of genetic height potential, in familial short stature the bone age would be appropriate for chronological age, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible diagnosis in a short child. However, it would typically present with a more pronounced decline in growth velocity than seen here. Formal diagnosis would require comprehensive endocrine testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKlinefelter syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a chromosomal abnormality (47XXY) that typically produces tall stature rather than short stature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe term \u003Cstrong\u003Epoor growth\u003C/strong\u003E describes a child who has fallen below two percentile lines from a previously well-tracking growth chart. In this case, the patient has been consistently tracking along the 3rd percentile without crossing percentile lines.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Constitutional delay is characterised by a short child with delayed bone age who is otherwise well and has a good height prognosis.","Familial short stature would have an appropriate bone age for chronological age.","Growth hormone deficiency typically presents with a decline in growth velocity and requires endocrine testing to diagnose.","Klinefelter syndrome (47XXY) typically produces tall rather than short stature.","Poor growth describes a child who has fallen below two percentile lines from a previously well-tracking growth chart."],"references":["Simm PJ, Werther GA. Child and adolescent growth disorders. Australian Family Physician. 2005; 34(9): 731-736."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"378"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30389"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-15T18:23:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-05-15T18:23:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"378"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45468"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"rela